The music Bolivia has long history Out all the Andean countries Bolivia remains perhaps the most culturally linked the indigenous peoples Like most its neighbors Bolivia was long dominated Spain and its attendant culture Even after independence Bolivian music was largely based European forms 1952 revolution established nationalistic reforms which included cultural and political awareness the Aymara and Quechua natives Intellectuals the country began wearing ponchos and otherwise associating themselves with native cultures and the new government promoted native folklore among other methods establishing folklore department the Bolivian Ministry Education Awareness native music spirituality and art continued into the 1960s 1965 Edgar Yayo Jofr formed quartet called Los Jairas Paz With Bolivian folk music gaining popularity throughout the country Jofr along with Alfredo Dominguez Ernesto Cavour Julio Godoy and Gilbert Favre used traditional music modified forms appeal urbandwellers and Europeans Later groups like Wara Khanata Paja Brava Savia Andina and especially Los Kjarkas and Kalamarka helped further refine this fusion Following close but different path groups and singers like Luzmila Carpio Ruphay and Grupo Aymara started touring abroad and gained international praise for their compositions tunes that have brought indigenous Bolivian culture and history the worlds attention Los Kjarkas consists brothers the Hermosas who play primarily Huayo more rarely sayas These are both dance music influenced both native forms well African music imported Bolivia with slavery Los Kjarkas are known internationally for their Caporales classic Llorando fue which was adopted and transformed the popular beginning the lambada dance craze the 1980s along with forr and carimbo northern Brazil The song was popularized French group resulting successful lawsuit from the Hermosa brothersKalamarka was founded 1984 Hugo Gutierrez and Rodolfo Choque They fusion folk instruments such Zampoa Quena Charango and Bombo with modern instruments creating beautiful musica andina Their famous songs are Cuando Florezca Chuo and Ama Ama AmazonasIn the 1980s Chilean nueva cancin was imported Bolivia and changed into canto nuevo which was popularized performers like Emma Junaro Traditional Bolivian and other South American musical instruments include the charango charangn ronroco hualaycho zampoa quena bombo huancara reco reco chiapya box pinquillo tarka toyos pututu Andean saxophone and Chajchas well European musical instruments such the violin and guitar Musical forms such the Bailecito Kullawada Tonada directly Tinku Taquirari Carnavalito Lamento AfroBolivian Saya Tuntuna Taki Taki and Cueca are prominently featured Bolivias cultural music 